            <div class="container">
                <h2 class="text-information-title">Basic design principles</h2>
                <p class="text-information">Data table block body</p>
                <p class="text-information">Each stormwater collection system consists of at least the following components :</p>
                <p class="text-information">Amount of rain</p>
                <p class="text-information">The catchment area or roof surface to collect rainwater.</p>
                <p class="text-information">Distribution system (gutter) to transport water from the roof or collection surface to the storage tank.</p>
                <p class="text-information">Storage tank or cistern to store water until use.</p>
                <p class="text-information">A extraction device (depending on the location of the tank - can be a hose, wire and bucket, or a pump (HATUM & WORM 2006); or an osmosis device in which case the collected water is used for extraction. replenishment of well or groundwater (see also surface or subsurface artificial groundwater recharge).</p>
                <div class="col-sm-5">
                    <img class="image" src="../image/Picture4.png" alt="">
                </div>
                <b>Catchment area</b>
                <p class="text-information">Data sheet block bodyPlastic panels are installed to enhance the catchment area</p>
                <p class="text-information">The catchment area is expanded. </p>
                <p class="text-information">To 'fit', the roof must be made of some hard material that is impervious to rainwater or contamination when water flows. Therefore, tile, sheet metal and most plastics are suitable,while grass and palm leaf roofs are generally not suitable .If a roof does not provide enough basin area, plastic panels can be used to enlarge the basin surface as shown on the next figure. </p>
                <div class="col-sm-5">
                    <img class="image" src="../image/Picture3.png" alt="">
                </div>
                <b>System :</b>
                <p class="text-information">Data table block body</p>
                <p class="text-information">Distribution systems from rural rooftop basins typically include gutters that hang from the sides of the roof slope toward the downpipe and cistern. Gutters are used to transport rainwater from the roof to the storage tank. Gutters come in a variety of shapes and forms, from factory-made PVC similar to those used in water distribution systems to homemade gutters made of bamboo or folded metal. Gutters are usually fixed to the building directly under the roof and catch water as it falls from the roof.</p>
                <div class="col-sm-5">
                    <img class="image" src="../image/Picture2.png" alt="">
                </div>
                <p class="text-information">Debris, dirt, dust and manure will settle on the roof of a building or other collection area. When the first rains come, these unwanted substances are washed into the tank. This will cause the water to become contaminated and degrade in quality. As a result, many RWH systems incorporate a system to redirect this 'first flush' water so it doesn't enter the tank. These systems are known as primary discharge devices.</p>
                <div class="col-sm-5">
                    <img class="image" src="../image/Picture1.png" alt="">
                </div>
                <h4>Different Methods To Collect Rainwater In Residential Areas:</h4>
                <b>RAIN BARRELS</b>
                <p class="text-information">This method is the most common and one that many people are familiar with. This involves installing a barrel at a gutter downspout to collect rainwater. The actual barrel may be a recycled barrel or a new commercially available rain barrel.</p>
                <dl>
                    <dt>Pros:</dt>
                    <dd>Easily implemented by anyone at any residence</dd>
                    <dd>Barrels are readily available in your community or at various stores & websites</dd>
                    <dd>Barrels don<sup>'</sup>t take up much space so they can fit into any situation</dd>
                </dl>
                <dl>
                    <dt>Cons:</dt>
                    <dd>Capacity is generally only 50 to 100 gallons</dd>
                    <dd>Easily overflows and wastes collection opportunities</dd>
                </dl>
                <div class="col-sm-5">
                    <img class="image" src="../image/Picture5.png" alt="">
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div> 
    <hr>
            <!-- new 4 hien tren man hinh chinh-->
    <div class="container" id="section4">
        <div class="col-sm_5">
            <h2 class="text-information-title">Rainwater Harvesting in Commercial area</h2>
            <p class="text-information">
                As the population grows, cities and suburbs expand with more buildings and so the demand for water continues to increase. The installation of a rainwater collection system is becoming increasingly important for businesses and commercial organizations. Rainwater harvesting is the first solution in a water management strategy for commercial, public and residential buildings. <br>
                If you have a commercial property then you can save millions of gallons of drinking water each year with an eco-friendly approach known as rainwater harvesting. If you are looking for relevant information on rainwater harvesting then you are at the right place to get it. Rainwater collection system is a very cost-effective solution that brings great benefits to commercial buildings such as: office buildings, schools, hotels, resorts, hospitals, homes. goods, etc.
            </p>
            <div class="col-sm-5">

                <img class="image" src="../image/pic 18.jpg" alt="" >
            
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
    <br>
    <div class="col-sm-2">
        <button class="btn btn-primary" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#multiCollapseExample4" 
        aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="multiCollapseExample4">Read more</button>
         </div>
            <!-- thong tin trong new 4 khi an vao button-->
    <div class="collapse multi-collapse" id="multiCollapseExample4">
        <div class="card card-body">
            <div class="container">
                <b>Rainwater harvesting: An effective solution for commercial users</b>
                <p class="text-information">Rainwater harvesting (RWH) systems are gradually becoming part of sustainable water management practices. Rainwater harvesting is a process of collecting, storing and reusing rainwater. Rainwater harvesting is one of the simplest ways for us to live sustainably with nature. Rainwater collection systems work by collecting rainwater from roof gutters, filtering it, and storing the water in a storage tank.</p>
                <p class="text-information">Rainwater extraction is becoming popular leading to ecological conservation. Most commercial buildings use a significant amount of water and energy in their daily operations. Rainwater collection is an old and effective technique of collecting rainwater during the rainy season for later use. The ecological benefit of a rainwater harvesting system for commercial buildings is that it will significantly reduce the amount of water used from the grid.</p>
                <div class="col-sm-5">

                    <img class="image" src="../image/pic 19.jpg" alt="" >
                
                </div>
                <b style="padding-top:10px ;">Rainwater harvesting methods for commercial buildings</b>
                <p class="text-information">Surface rainwater harvesting and rooftop harvesting are the two main rainwater harvesting methods where rooftop harvesting is the most preferred rainwater harvesting method for commercial buildings. The basic components of this system are: basin, gutter, down pipe, storage tank and distribution system. The catchment area that receives direct rainfall where downspouts and pipes bring water from the surface of the basin to a reservoir that may be located above ground or below ground. Finally, the collected rainwater will be filtered and distributed to the point of use through a distribution system.</p>
                <div class="col-sm-5">

                <img class="image" src="../image/pic 20.jpg" alt="" >
                
                </div>
                <p class="text-information">It can supply non-potable water to meet different needs of commercial building such as toilet flushing, washing, gardening and so on.</p>
                <b>Benefits of rainwater harvesting for commercial buildings</b>
                <p class="text-information">The efficient use of water is becoming increasingly important. Rainwater harvesting is an important part of determining how environmentally friendly a building is. Rainwater harvesting systems allow for the collection, conservation and reuse of rainwater that falls on the roof area of a building and it has significant potential to provide economic and environmental benefits. The benefits of RWH for commercial buildings are numerous and let's take a look:</p>
                <div class="col-sm-5">

                    <img class="image" src="../image/pic 21.jpg" alt="" >
                
                </div>
                <br>
                <div class="col-sm-5">

                    <img class="image" src="../image/pic 22.jpg" alt="" >
                
                </div>
                <br>
                <div class="col-sm-5">

                    <img class="image" src="../image/pic 23.jpg" alt="" >
                
                </div>
                <br>
                <div class="col-sm-5">

                    <img class="image" src="../image/pic 24.png" alt="" >
                
                </div>

                <ol>
                    <li>It can reduce the main water supply by 40-50%</li>
                    <li>It reduces runoff and its harmful effects</li>
                    <li>RWH promotes both water and energy conservation</li>
                    <li>The system is easy to install, operate and maintain</li>
                    <li>Can be used for some purposes other than drinks</li>
                    <li>It also helps to gain authentic corporate sustainability information</li>
                    <li>The growing demand for water can be met</li>
                    <li>It saves a lot of money on water</li>
                </ol>
                <blockquote><b>“It is a wise decision to set up a rainwater collection system for your commercial buildings to overcome the water shortage problem!”</b></blockquote>




















